        "description": "Richardson extrapolation-based GCI computed on three systematically refined meshes (coarse ~80k, medium ~320k, fine ~1.28M elements); GCI on stiffness QoI < 1.5% and on yield force QoI < 2.0%; mesh convergence plots archived in technical file."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed with a refinement ratio of 2. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.1% (stiffness) and 1.7% (yield force), both below the 2% threshold. The production mesh (medium, ~320k elements) was selected as the converged baseline. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The FEA model uses a direct sparse solver (Ansys Sparse Direct) for a deterministic implicit-static structural analysis. There are no iterative convergence tolerances that introduce solver-level numerical error beyond floating-point round-off, which is bounded by the code-verification activities already documented under the Numerical code verification factor. Solver error as a distinct credibility factor is therefore not applicable to this analysis type; the ASME V&V 40 guidance notes that this factor is primarily relevant to iterative or time-marching solvers where residual tolerance and time-step error interact."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The analysis is executed within a controlled regulatory submission workflow: a single qualified analyst team (FDA OSEL) performed all simulations using a locked, version-tagged analysis script with no manual geometry or boundary-condition entry at runtime. There is no user-selectable model configuration that could introduce operator-driven variation beyond what is captured by the SQA and reproducibility checks. Use error as a standalone factor does not add discriminating credibility information in this tightly controlled single-analyst context and is therefore not applicable."
    },
    {
